## Setup

Create an isolated worktree before doing anything else:

```bash
cd <repo path>
git fetch origin
git worktree add .claude/worktrees/<id>-<slug> -b {{ .ado.branchPrefix }}<id>-<slug> origin/master
```

Always branch from `origin/master` (or `origin/main` — check which exists) so you have the latest remote state. Never branch from the local `master` — it may be stale.

All subsequent work happens inside the worktree. Set your working directory:

```bash
cd <repo path>/.claude/worktrees/<id>-<slug>
```

## Instructions

1. Read the repo's CLAUDE.md for build/test/lint commands
2. Run the full test suite. All tests MUST pass before you write any code. If tests fail on a clean checkout, stop and report the failures — do not proceed.
3. Understand the codebase area relevant to this bug/task
4. Work through the plan one unit at a time. For each unit:
   a. Write a failing test that reproduces the bug or validates the change (RED)
   b. Implement the minimal fix/feature to make the test pass (GREEN)
   c. Refactor if needed while keeping tests green
   d. Run the full test suite — all tests must pass
   e. Commit with a descriptive message for that unit. Do NOT use `AB#` prefixes — work items are linked via the PR, not commit messages.

   Each commit should be a single logical change (bisectable). Split:
   - Rename/move separate from behavior changes
   - Test infrastructure separate from test implementations
   - Config changes separate from code that uses them

5. **Self-review**: run `git diff main...HEAD` and evaluate your changes on:
   - **Correctness**: does this fix/implement the work item?
   - **Scope**: are ALL changes related to this work item? Compare the work item description to your diff — flag and revert any unrelated file changes before proceeding.
   - **Tests**: are existing tests passing? Are new tests needed and present?
   - **Style**: does the code match the repo's conventions?

   Score 0-100. If score < 80, fix issues before proceeding. Note the score in your PR description.

6. Push branch and open a DRAFT PR:
   a. Check the repo for PR conventions before creating. Look for:
      - PR template (`.azuredevops/pull_request_template.md`, `.github/pull_request_template.md`)
      - PR-related skills (e.g., `/create-pr`)
      - PR instructions in the repo's CLAUDE.md
   b. If a PR skill or template exists, use it — fill out all required sections.
   c. If none exist, create a draft PR with a descriptive title (no `AB#` prefix) via `az repos pr create --work-items <ID>`.
   d. Always: draft only, link work items, no `AB#` prefix in the title.
7. **Clean up worktree** — the code now lives on the remote branch, so the local worktree is no longer needed:
   ```bash
   cd <repo path>
   git worktree remove .claude/worktrees/<id>-<slug>
   ```
8. Post an ADO comment on the work item with: summary of changes, PR link, review score, open questions
9. Update ADO work item state to Active if currently Proposed

## Issue classification

When you encounter issues during implementation:
- **AUTO-FIX**: Mechanical issues (lint errors, formatting, obvious typos, missing imports) — fix automatically without stopping.
- **ASK**: Judgment calls (architecture decisions, API design, unclear requirements, multiple valid approaches) — stop, document the question, and report as `NEEDS_CONTEXT`.

## Notifications
Post to Teams when: starting work, opening a PR, blocked/need help, or done.
```bash
az rest --method POST \
  --url "https://graph.microsoft.com/v1.0/teams/{{ .teams.teamId }}/channels/{{ .teams.channelId }}/messages" \
  --headers "Content-Type=application/json" \
  --body '{"body":{"contentType":"html","content":"<b>[WI#<ID>]</b> <status message>"}}'
```

## Browser Queue (WSL <-> Windows handoff)
When you need browser access (wiki, authenticated pages, UI verification), use the
browser queue instead of blocking. This lets a Windows Claude session with `/chrome`
handle the browser work asynchronously.

**Request a browser task:**
1. Write a request file to `~/cockpit/state/browser-queue/<WI-ID>-<slug>.request.md`:
   ```markdown
   # Browser Request: WI#<ID>
   - Work Item: <ID>
   - Agent Task: <task-id if available>
   - Created: <ISO timestamp>

   ## What I Need
   <Specific URL to visit, what to look for, what to extract or verify>

   ## Context
   <Why this is needed — what the agent is trying to accomplish>
   ```
2. Post to Teams:
   ```
   <b>[WI#<ID>] [NEEDS BROWSER]</b> <what you need>
   ```
3. Continue with any remaining non-browser work. Do NOT block.

## Shell Commands
- After setup, your working directory is the worktree. Run git/yarn commands directly (e.g. `git status`, `yarn lint`).
- NEVER chain commands with `&&` or `;` — run each as a separate Bash call.

## Safety
- ONLY modify files related to this work item
- ONLY push to branch: {{ .ado.branchPrefix }}<id>-<slug>
- ONLY open DRAFT PRs — never publish or merge
- If blocked or uncertain, stop and document findings

## Terminal Status

When finished, you MUST report one of these statuses:

- **DONE** — Work item implemented, tests pass, PR opened. Evidence: PR link, test results, review score.
- **DONE_WITH_CONCERNS** — PR opened but something is uncertain (incomplete test coverage, edge case not handled, assumption made). Evidence: what was done, what's uncertain, recommended follow-up.
- **BLOCKED** — Cannot proceed. Evidence: what was tried, what's blocking, recommended next steps.
- **NEEDS_CONTEXT** — Hit a judgment call that requires human input. Evidence: the specific question, options considered, recommendation.

Format:
```
## Terminal Status: <STATUS>
- Evidence: <what was done/found>
- Next steps: <what remains, if anything>
```
